solutions.content:
The idea is like many others pointed out  - to use DP and calculate prefix sums either for rows or for columns, I used rows below. 

After that by changing the width of the submatrix (imaging vertically slicing it),we go from top to the bottom processing each row and calculate the sum of the submatrix composed of the intervals limited by the left and right border of the slice. Prefix sums in dp array calculated before help here. What we get as a result is a prefix sum of submatrices.

For every such submatrix we check if we could start somewhere in the past and sum to the target by using a hashtable where we store the count of every submatrix prefix we've seen.

We essentially check if we've seen the prefix = currentsum-target before and how many times and sum these values to get the answer. Hope it helps!

```
public class Solution {
    public int NumSubmatrixSumTarget(int[][] matrix, int target) 
    {
        if(matrix==null || matrix.Length ==0)
        {
            return 0;
        }

        int w = matrix[0].Length;
        int h = matrix.Length;

        // use new matrix, however if reuseif allowed it's possible to have O(1) space
        // by overwriting the values in the source matrix
        int[,] dp = new int[h,w+1];

        for (int i = 0; i < h; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < w; j++) {
                //prefix sum for the row
                dp[i,j+1] = dp[i,j] + matrix[i][j];
            }
        }

        // holds the remainder sums of the matrices which could serve as a
        // starting point for our submatrix.
        Dictionary<int, int> starts = new Dictionary<int,int>();

        int res = 0;
        // iterate through all possible vertical submatrices
        for (int i = 1; i <= w; i++) 
        {
            for (int j = i; j <= w; j++) 
            {
                starts.Clear();
                starts[0] = 1;

                // holds the submatrix sum, it's the frontier of the imaginary 1D array where each
                // element is a matrix sum seen up and including this element, can be seen as a prefix sum of submatrices
                int end = 0;

                for (int k = 0; k < h; k++) 
                {
                    // find the sum of the matrix elements up to this point,
                    // by summing up the interval sums [i,j] row by row using the prefix sums calculated before
                    end += dp[k,j] - dp[k,i - 1];

                    // "start" prefix sum, 
                    // it means that  if somewhere in the past we saw sum==start -> 
                    // we found a suitable matrix now as we could start from there.
                    // end-start = target => start = end - target;
                    int start = end - target; 

                    // add the number of matrices we've seen so far, so that they had the sum equal to the
                    // complement we need
                    res += starts.ContainsKey(start) ? starts[start]: 0;

                    // log the sum for the current matrix, 
                    // it will serve as a start prefix sum ("start") later when will be checking for possible complements
                    starts[end] = (starts.ContainsKey(end) ? starts[end]+1 : 1);                 
                }
            }
        }            

        return res;
    }
}
```

