solutions.content:
The principal observation here is that this problem is reducable to solving multiple problems of the type [560. Subarray Sum Equals K](https://leetcode.com/problems/subarray-sum-equals-k/) . How?

- Finding all sub-matrices that sum to `target` can be tackled by going over all sub-matrices. We can do this traversal by consider all submatrices whose ends lie between column indices `lo` and `hi` (inclusive and `lo <= hi`) for all valid pairs of column indices `(lo, hi)`. We argue that each such **sub-problem** (i.e. all sub-matrices between a given pair of column indices `(lo, hi)` is an instance of [560. Subarray Sum Equals K](https://leetcode.com/problems/subarray-sum-equals-k/) . This we show below.
- Imagine that we have calculated the **prefix-sum for each row** of the `matrix` i.e. `sum[r][c]` holds the sum `matrix[r][0] + matrix[r][1] + ... + matrix[r][c]` for all `(r, c)`. (We don't create a separate 2D array `sum` for this, but do it in-place in the input 2D array `matrix` itself, but using a separate 2D array avoids confusion when explaining the concept).
- Now, consider a pair of columns `lo` and `hi`. For each such pair, we can create an array (say `submat` such that `submat[r] = sum[r][hi] - sum[r][lo-1]` i.e. `submat[r]` is the sum of all values in the row `r` of the original matrix between columns `lo` and `hi` (inclusive). Finding all non-empty subarrays in `submat` that sum to target is precisely what we're looking for as the **sub-problem**.
- We use the class `SubarraySumCount` that abstracts away the details of [560. Subarray Sum Equals K](https://leetcode.com/problems/subarray-sum-equals-k/) in a clean interface.

```
/*
// Usage:
    SubarraySumCount s {target};
    for(auto const &v : values)
        s.add(v);
    auto res = s.count();
// `res` holds the count of all non-empty subarrays from `values`
// that have a sum equal to `target`

*/

template <typename T>
class SubarraySumCount {
    static_assert(is_integral_v<T>, "Must specify an Integral Type");

    unordered_map<T, size_t> ct;
    T target;
    T cum {0};
    size_t res {0};
public:
    SubarraySumCount(const T &target) : target(target) {
        ct[0] = 1;
    }

    inline void add(const T& val) {
        cum += val;
        auto const &complement = cum - target;
        if(auto it = ct.find(complement); it != ct.end())
            res += it->second;
        ct[cum]++;
    }

    inline size_t count() const {
        return res;
    }

    void reset() {
        ct.clear();
        cum = 0;
        res = 0;

        ct[0] = 1;
    }
};

class Solution {
public:
    int numSubmatrixSumTarget(vector<vector<int>>& matrix, int target) {
        const int rows = matrix.size();
        const int cols = matrix[0].size();

        // row-wise prefix sums
        for(auto &row : matrix)
            partial_sum(begin(row), end(row), begin(row));

        int res {0};
		// [CHOICE-A]: Single `SubarraySumCount` object during this function's lifetime that is `reset()`
		// multiple times
        SubarraySumCount s {target};

        for(int lo = 0; lo < cols; lo++) {
            for(int hi = lo; hi < cols; hi++) {
			    // [CHOICE-B]: Multiple `SubarraySumCount` objects during function's lifetime
				// Once per pair of column indices that is destroyed rather than being `reset`.
				// SubarraySumCount s {target};
                for(int r = 0; r < rows; r++)
                    s.add(matrix[r][hi] - (lo > 0 ? matrix[r][lo-1] : 0));
                res += s.count();
                // [CHOICE-A]
				s.reset();
            }
        }

        return res;
    }
};
```

Time-Complexity: `O(cols * cols * rows)`
Space-Complexity: Ignoring the in-place use of the input `matrix`
- Choice **A**: `O(cols * cols * rows)` in worst case (Is the time better though? IDK.)
- Choice **B**: `O(rows)` in worst case.

