solutions.content:
Question :- To find number of subarrays with sum = target. 

Concept :- We have total 3 ways to do :- One is sliding window, second is niave by taking all possible subarrays and third is O(n) approach using prefix sum and map which stores all occured prefix sums till current index.

So, first two approaches are straightforward, lets discuss third approach :-

Crux :- We iterate from left to right and continuously calculate prefix sum at each index and also storing them in a map and also at current index, we apply map.find(prefix sum - target), if found then we increment our answer or count by map[prefix sum - target] means frequency of compliment (prefix sum - target) already occured.

What it indicates :- Suppose we have an array and we are at current index 5, means we have already stored all previous prefix sums in map. So, current prefix sum - target = value and if this value exists in map, means the subarray from the index after that found previous sum till current index has a sum = target.

So, if this value has occured for suppose 3 times, means there are 3 subarays which are ending at current index with sum = target and starting after the index till which previous found value has occured.

So, in this way we can calculate all the subarrays with sum = target.



Now, we have to just use this concept to solve it for a matrix :-

Suppose we have a matrix of size (n * m) , means each row has m elements. 
Think matrix as a 1d array, BUT we have to find what elements actually matching the analogy with 1d array elements which we discussed above then only we can solve it for matrix.

So, if we think, we can use each row with total m^2 ranges from any left column till any right column, so for this we use all pairs of columns as extremes and consider the range of all rows between current pair of columns inclusive both.

So, the sum of each row elements in the given current range will be considered as the analogy elements of a 1d array.

So for any current range, we have n (number of rows of matrix) elements which are actually the sum of elements in this range for each ith row.

Now apply same concept as we did in 1d array case, the only difference is that there we had only 1 occurence of working, here we have m^2 occurences of working, for each possible range of row.

NOTE :- Why we are considering all possible ranges in each row? 

Suppose we have 5 columns or 5 elements in each row then we can select any possible range of continuous elements to form a submatrix whose column length will be this range's length.



```
class Solution {
public:
    int numSubmatrixSumTarget(vector<vector<int>>& matrix, int target) {
        int n = matrix.size();
        int m = matrix[0].size();

        vector<vector<int>> prefix_row(n,vector<int>(m));

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            for(int j=0;j<m;j++)
            {
                if(j == 0)
                {
                    prefix_row[i][j] = matrix[i][j];
                }
                else
                {
                    prefix_row[i][j] = prefix_row[i][j-1] + matrix[i][j];
                }
            }
        }

        int res = 0;

        for(int lc=0;lc<m;lc++)
        {
            for(int rc=lc;rc<m;rc++)
            {
                map<int,int> m;
                int prefix = 0;

                m[0] = 1;

                for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
                {
                    if(lc == 0)
                    {
                        prefix += prefix_row[i][rc];
                    }
                    else
                    {
                        prefix += prefix_row[i][rc] - prefix_row[i][lc - 1];
                    }

                    if(m.find(prefix - target) != m.end())
                    {
                        res += m[prefix - target];
                    }

                    m[prefix]++;
                }
            }
        }

        return res;

    }
};
```

