solutions.content:
Trying brute-force with prefixes in different languages, i.e., caclulating 2D prefix sums and iterating over every submatrice. 
This is a great example to see how Python execution time suffers when using plain `for` loops.
Doing this in Java, it succeeds all tests after 250 ms. Doing the same in Python3 fails with `Time Limit Exceeded`, i.e., >10s. 

**Java 250 ms**
```
class Solution {
    public int numSubmatrixSumTarget(int[][] matrix, int target) {
        int m = matrix.length;
        int n = matrix[0].length;
        int[][] prefixes = calculatePrefixes(matrix);
        int ans = 0;
        for(int i=1; i<=m; i++) {
            for(int j=1; j<=n; j++) {
                for(int a=i; a<=m; a++) {
                    for(int b=j; b<=n; b++) {
                        if(prefixes[a][b] - prefixes[i-1][b] - prefixes[a][j-1] + prefixes[i-1][j-1] == target) {
                            ans += 1;
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }

    private int[][] calculatePrefixes(int[][] matrix) {
        int[][] prefixes = new int[matrix.length + 1][matrix[0].length + 1];
        prefixes[0] = new int[matrix[0].length + 1];
        for(int i=0; i<=matrix[0].length; i++) {
            prefixes[0][i] = 0;
        }

        for(int i=1; i<=matrix.length; i++) {
            prefixes[i][0] = 0;
            for(int j=1; j<=matrix[0].length; j++) {
                prefixes[i][j] = prefixes[i][j-1] + matrix[i-1][j-1];
            }
        }

        for(int j=1; j<=matrix[0].length; j++) {
            for(int i=1; i<=matrix.length; i++) {
                prefixes[i][j] += prefixes[i-1][j];
            }
        }

        return prefixes;
    }
}
```

**Python3 - Time Limit Exceeded**
```
class Solution:
    def numSubmatrixSumTarget(self, matrix: List[List[int]], target: int) -> int:
        m, n = len(matrix), len(matrix[0])
        ans = 0

        # 2d prefix sums with [0] prefix:
        # accumulate rows -> transpose -> accumulate rows -> transpose
		# calculating the 2D prefixes takes around 10-20 ms
        acc_rows = [list(accumulate(row)) for row in matrix]
        transposed = [list(tup) for tup in zip(*acc_rows)]
        acc_rows = [[0]*m] + [list(accumulate(row)) for row in transposed]
        prefixes = [[0]*(n+1)] + [list(tup) for tup in zip(*acc_rows)]

		# access to local variables is much faster than to global
		r = range

        # Iterate over all submatrices
        for i in r(1, m+1):
            for j in r(1, n+1):
                for a in r(i, m+1):
                    for b in r(j, n+1):
                        if prefixes[a][b] - prefixes[i-1][b] - prefixes[a][j-1] + prefixes[i-1][j-1] == target:
                            ans += 1
        return ans
```

Calculating the 2D prefixes takes up to 20 ms, so that is not the core problem here. In general Python3 execution time suffers heavily from accessing attributes or making function calls. Further, plain `for` loops are pretty slow too compared to built-in functions and list comprehension. Best performance boost can be gained by using numpy arrays, but that is also more complex than using plain built-in `for` loops.

